      "text": "Partition Table -> ",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Partition Table -> ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "Qes99GuqJx94I6K8uy0ob",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1045.608467671342,
      "y": 36055.40919892791,
      "width": 1111,
      "height": 1075,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#b2f2bb",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bQM",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 97266276,
      "version": 3670,
      "versionNonce": 225756937,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1775105901858,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "When we create partitions, by default in machine we can only create 4 partitions \nWhy ? Why only 4 partitions ?\nthe size of partition table is already fixed, we can't change this file size. And because\nthe file size is fixed, it can only take 4 entries, because it can only take 4 entries\nwe can only created 4 partitions, No more than 4.\n\nWhat happen if we want to create more that 4 partitions, Which means we can create\n3 regular partition, whihc we also call that primary partitions\n\nWhat happens if we want to create more that 4 partitions ?\n    In that case we are going to create atleast there is 1 partition that we can choose\nand create it something called as extended partition\n\nWhat happens when we create a extended partition, A table gets created over extended partition\nand this table now can have entries of 60 more partitions, It more like partition is created\nbut partition has its own partition table than can have 60 more entries, Why only 60  because\nfile size is limited. It can only take 60 entries, So we can create 60 more partitions.\nSo in a way what is maximumm partitions we can create in a Linux machine or any machine -> \nwe can create 60 + 4 -> 64\nAnd how many partitions we can use 63 becuase 64th partition is already use to create other\npartitions.\n\nQ -> Why partition table can create only 4 partitions but extended can create 60? due to legacy\nsystem has 4 partion entries in partition table, in these 4 only 1 can be extended not other\n\n\nLets say we have a external HDD, I connect to my system but this external HDD somewhere has to\nconnect with my existing Operating system because without that existing operating system we dont\nhave even a way to interact with this external HDD, SO it has to connect with our Current OS\nwhich means some folde/directory must be there where if I start writing data, it will start going in \nmy external HDD, So it would not be saved in our disk, it will be going in my external HDD.\nFor example if we connect it, in windows it becomes my E drive so that E drive is nothing but a \nfolder/directory now and that directory just tells me that when you start writing over me , I will\nbe pushing the data to External HDD. Creating E drive will acts like a pointer and redirect our\nstorage from our OS to external HDD this thing is called mount point\n\nIN Linux all our storage and everything starts from /. So our slash becomes 1 mount point.\nLets say our whole HDD is there, created multiple partitions\nSo everything that we will write will go inside / and we will able to see as /bin or /bin/date\n\nmount point is just a pointer, we have C , D, E partition in windows, OS is by default in C drive\nif we want to create D and E basically those are also inside C, where there are mount point for \nD and E if we will write anything there they will redirect to D and E.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "When we create partitions, by default in machine we can only create 4 partitions \nWhy ? Why only 4 partitions ?\nthe size of partition table is already fixed, we can't change this file size. And because\nthe file size is fixed, it can only take 4 entries, because it can only take 4 entries\nwe can only created 4 partitions, No more than 4.\n\nWhat happen if we want to create more that 4 partitions, Which means we can create\n3 regular partition, whihc we also call that primary partitions\n\nWhat happens if we want to create more that 4 partitions ?\n    In that case we are going to create atleast there is 1 partition that we can choose\nand create it something called as extended partition\n\nWhat happens when we create a extended partition, A table gets created over extended partition\nand this table now can have entries of 60 more partitions, It more like partition is created\nbut partition has its own partition table than can have 60 more entries, Why only 60  because\nfile size is limited. It can only take 60 entries, So we can create 60 more partitions.\nSo in a way what is maximumm partitions we can create in a Linux machine or any machine -> \nwe can create 60 + 4 -> 64\nAnd how many partitions we can use 63 becuase 64th partition is already use to create other\npartitions.\n\nQ -> Why partition table can create only 4 partitions but extended can create 60? due to legacy\nsystem has 4 partion entries in partition table, in these 4 only 1 can be extended not other\n\n\nLets say we have a external HDD, I connect to my system but this external HDD somewhere has to\nconnect with my existing Operating system because without that existing operating system we dont\nhave even a way to interact with this external HDD, SO it has to connect with our Current OS\nwhich means some folde/directory must be there where if I start writing data, it will start going in \nmy external HDD, So it would not be saved in our disk, it will be going in my external HDD.\nFor example if we connect it, in windows it becomes my E drive so that E drive is nothing but a \nfolder/directory now and that directory just tells me that when you start writing over me , I will\nbe pushing the data to External HDD. Creating E drive will acts like a pointer and redirect our\nstorage from our OS to external HDD this thing is called mount point\n\nIN Linux all our storage and everything starts from /. So our slash becomes 1 mount point.\nLets say our whole HDD is there, created multiple partitions\nSo everything that we will write will go inside / and we will able to see as /bin or /bin/date\n\nmount point is just a pointer, we have C , D, E partition in windows, OS is by default in C drive\nif we want to create D and E basically those are also inside C, where there are mount point for \nD and E if we will write anything there they will redirect to D and E.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
