    {
      "id": "-ixhyiNDJu5uze5UIzTPa",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1071.866280171342,
      "y": 39697.97169892791,
      "width": 1056,
      "height": 350,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffec99",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bRA",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1721781720,
      "version": 1415,
      "versionNonce": 1889199463,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1775105901858,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "In start of Harddisk there is a table called partition table, this table is common for\nall partitions, all primary partitions are registered here in which 1 primary partition\nthat we can convert to being a extended partition that is also registered here it is one\nof them from primary partitions. There will be only 4 entries over partition table, because\nthe table size is max to this much only that it can only contain at max 4 intries. Which\nmeans we can create 4 partitions, Now if we want to create more partitions, we can define \nany of them as a extended partition. when we define a partition as a extended partition what\nhappen over there is we will have this partition in which one more table is created and that \nis our extended partition table. Now this epartition table can have 60 more entries, So likewise\nwe can create 60 more partition.\n\nPartition table will point us to extended partition table and this table will point us to \nextended partition 1, 2, 3.. 60, In this partition we will refer to our file system table.\nFS table will show us directories or whatever is the data that is kept inside that partition.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "In start of Harddisk there is a table called partition table, this table is common for\nall partitions, all primary partitions are registered here in which 1 primary partition\nthat we can convert to being a extended partition that is also registered here it is one\nof them from primary partitions. There will be only 4 entries over partition table, because\nthe table size is max to this much only that it can only contain at max 4 intries. Which\nmeans we can create 4 partitions, Now if we want to create more partitions, we can define \nany of them as a extended partition. when we define a partition as a extended partition what\nhappen over there is we will have this partition in which one more table is created and that \nis our extended partition table. Now this epartition table can have 60 more entries, So likewise\nwe can create 60 more partition.\n\nPartition table will point us to extended partition table and this table will point us to \nextended partition 1, 2, 3.. 60, In this partition we will refer to our file system table.\nFS table will show us directories or whatever is the data that is kept inside that partition.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
