      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1775105901859,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "we will mount in Desktop -> Desktop is present in /home/ubuntu\nmkdir /home/ubuntu/data -> create directory\nmount /dev/vg1/lv1 /home/ubuntu/data -> this will mount lv1 to data directory",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "we will mount in Desktop -> Desktop is present in /home/ubuntu\nmkdir /home/ubuntu/data -> create directory\nmount /dev/vg1/lv1 /home/ubuntu/data -> this will mount lv1 to data directory",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "25iJYW1oh4dJRKZlyFawd",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 911.3740926713419,
      "y": 48060.83888642791,
      "width": 1056,
      "height": 50,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bTH",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 523699769,
      "version": 203,
      "versionNonce": 418208615,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1775105901859,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Q Why we chosen ext4 as file system not other? we could have used fact whihc is famously used in\nLinux or we could have used NTFS famously used in windows and Linux both why ext4?",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Q Why we chosen ext4 as file system not other? we could have used fact whihc is famously used in\nLinux or we could have used NTFS famously used in windows and Linux both why ext4?",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "k0VZa4Pc4rcA0GYwEdgbu",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 982.4365926713419,
      "y": 48133.27638642791,
      "width": 1067,
      "height": 350,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bTI",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1051228889,
      "version": 1246,
      "versionNonce": 1001763465,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1775105901859,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Lets say we are providing someone a drive storage and that storage is full they are asking\nus to expand their storage size , we can't say like that please delete all data we are giving\nyou a new disk, that will be a bad idea\nwhat we do is that we have given them some current storage and we will just expand or add to \ntheir storage, to add that in LVM or LV there is a command called lvextend practice this after\nsession and we can extend the size of curren LV, Likewize our VG can also be full then what\nwe will do,we will add one more partition and create PV3 , Now there is a command called as\nvgextend that helps to extend the size of current vg by adding more PVs to it.\nNow we can use lvextend since we have space in our vg now.\nWithout unmounting, without changing anything regarding the disk, without reformating or without\ndoing any changes this increase happen on the fly, on the go. On the fly the size of disk will be\nincreased without impacting use anyhow.\nSimilarily we can do lvreduce or vgreduce but in reduction obviously there is a possibility of\ndata loss.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Lets say we are providing someone a drive storage and that storage is full they are asking\nus to expand their storage size , we can't say like that please delete all data we are giving\nyou a new disk, that will be a bad idea\nwhat we do is that we have given them some current storage and we will just expand or add to \ntheir storage, to add that in LVM or LV there is a command called lvextend practice this after\nsession and we can extend the size of curren LV, Likewize our VG can also be full then what\nwe will do,we will add one more partition and create PV3 , Now there is a command called as\nvgextend that helps to extend the size of current vg by adding more PVs to it.\nNow we can use lvextend since we have space in our vg now.\nWithout unmounting, without changing anything regarding the disk, without reformating or without\ndoing any changes this increase happen on the fly, on the go. On the fly the size of disk will be\nincreased without impacting use anyhow.\nSimilarily we can do lvreduce or vgreduce but in reduction obviously there is a possibility of\ndata loss.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
